Thyroid cartilage"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe thyroid gland originates from the \u003Cstrong\u003Eforamen caecum\u003C/strong\u003E at the base of the tongue, between the anterior two-thirds and posterior one-third. It descends through the developing neck anterior to the developing hyoid bone (the \u003Cstrong\u003Ehyoid bone\u003C/strong\u003E) and laryngeal cartilages (including the \u003Cstrong\u003Ethyroid cartilage\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Ecricoid cartilage\u003C/strong\u003E). The \u003Cstrong\u003Epyriform fossa\u003C/strong\u003E develops separately as part of the pharyngeal apparatus.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe path of descent forms the thyroglossal duct, which usually obliterates. Failure of complete obliteration can result in thyroglossal duct cysts. The foramen caecum remains as a small pit marking the original position of thyroid development.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The thyroid gland develops from the foramen caecum at the base of the tongue and migrates down the thyroglossal duct to reach its final position in the neck.","Understanding thyroid embryology is crucial for explaining the anatomical basis of thyroglossal duct cysts and ectopic thyroid tissue."],"references":["Moran C, Schoenmakers N, Visser WE, Schoenmakers E, Agostini M, Chatterjee K. Genetic disorders of thyroid development, hormone biosynthesis and signalling. Clin Endocrinol (Oxf). 2022 Oct;97(4):502-514. doi: 10.1111/cen.14817. Epub 2022 Sep 5. PMID: 35999191; PMCID: PMC9544560","Rosen RD, Sapra A. Embryology, Thyroid. [Updated 2023 May 1]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK551611/","Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Netter Collection of Medical Illustrations: Endocrine System E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Wass, J. A., \u0026 Stewart, P. M. (Eds.). (2011). Oxford textbook of endocrinology and diabetes. Oxford University Press. USA"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52104"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15575"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52104","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52104"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-01T17:56:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-01T17:56:49+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8266"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66651"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags"